Fusion360

The implementation in Fusion360 is pretty simple:
-First you create a new sketch on the desired surface (right-click --> Create Sketch)
-Then you import the .svg (Insert SVG)
-scale the image (Scale Plane XY) to proportion and move to the desired spot
-hit OK and Stop Sketch

Now you have faces in the shape of the logo that you can select and pull with Q. E voilá, you've added a logo to a surface! :-)

title: Slotcar-Fahrwerk für Sauber Mercedes C-9 von Revell in 1:24

description.text:
Hallo,
hier also mein erstes Fahrwerk für ein Slotcar in 1:24.
Als Familienvater und Slotcarfan wurmt mich immer mehr wie teuer doch ein Fahrwerk
für so ein Slotcar ist.
Ich fahre beim Slottrack Niederberg http://www.slottrack-niederberg.de
Trotz sehr ungläubigen Blicken ...und starken Bedenken meiner Kollegen versuche ich mal den Bau eines 3D-Fahrwerks. Seit langem habe ich einen Revell Bausatz und Lexan-Deckel ( https://www.ebay.de/itm/Slotcar-Racing-Edition-No-7-Mercedes-C9-1-24/371931543998?ssPageName=STRK%3AMEBIDX%3AIT&_trksid=p2060353.m1438.l2649 ) eines Sauber Mercedes C-9 im Schrank welche dran glauben müssen :-)
Leider stellte sich nach den ersten Druckversuchen heraus das beide Deckel doch recht große Unterschiede in den Abmaßen haben, deshalb passt sich das Fahrwerk besser dem Revell-Deckel an obwohl für den Lexandeckel schon 1mm Führungen vorne und an den Seiten sind. Für den Lexan-Deckel muss ich noch das Fahrwerk nach vorne hin verlängern und nach hinten weiter ins Detail gehen...den Heckspoiler würde ich gerne mit integrieren.
Die Vorderachse ist federnd gelagert und in der Grundplatte sind Aussparungen für Gewichte. Alles ist für 3mm Wellen ausgelegt und wird mit den üblichen Kugellagern mit Aussend. 6mm gelagert. Als Motor dient ein Standart FOX Motor.

  • Die erste Probefahrt verlief schon einmal gut...obwohl ich nur zwei Gewichte zur Hand hatte. Das Slotcar ging ab wie ein Zäpfchen, nur fehlte durch zu wenig Gewicht natürlich der Gripp.

This is a set of rolling pin spacers to make evenly thick dough for my rolling pin that measures 54.25mm. They fit by pressure very snugly on each end. I printed these using a brim, so it added a slight bit of thickness to the ring that could be easily shaved off to account for any differences in thickness of the pin.
Included are a 1/8", 1/4" and a 1/2" version for different thicknesses.
The text is recessed in to one side. These were printed slowly with PETG which took about 90 minutes each and the numbers were filled using nail polish and then the flat surface was wiped with acetone. If you try this trick test your plastic with acetone before applying anything to your model. Acetone will melt ABS, and its not supposed to damage PLA, but I've ruined a piece before when it leeched the color out of it.

Two separate parts - each split into two halves - have to be mounted on the steering rod of the scooter. The upper part holds the wire and the lock in place and the lower part offers o hook around which the wire is wound when not in use. I combined four of them as you can see on the pictures.

It is designed to fit 7 "8 Pixel WS2812b Led-boards" (1 per segment) and therefore can display every color you like and you can break down animations to a single pixel.

I sourced them from aliexpress. The link below links to an offer of 10 pieces, feel free to compare prices and find other boards. They are available on black and white pcb's and keep in mind that it is never wrong to have some spare parts ;)

You may noticed... the diffusor is upside down so you have to rotate it in your slicer.
Print the SevenSegPanel once and, if you want, 7 of the SevenSegDiffusor to get one complete digit.

If you have printed the parts it is time to hotglue (a very small drop of glue is enough and if you end up having to change a module it makes everything much easier ;) ) the led boards into the frame. No need to worry about the direction as due to the printed pins it is not possible to mount them the wrong way. (of course you should check that the led is facing upwards ;) )

Now turn the display around and connect the modules in a serial manner together. Have a look at the picture to see how i have done this.

All you have to do now is to connect multiple displays together (if you built more than one) and connect the input to some sort of microcontroller.

description.text:
Update: I've added a drilling template to give a better chance to get the holes into the right places :)

This is a remix of MattyVee's brilliantly simple design. After having the tensioner in use on my Prusa MK3 for some time I've decided that it would be a great addition to my P3Steel as well. All solutions I've found for that printer were either clunky, wobbly or hard to get to (two screws under the heated bed etc).

There's one little problem with the P3Steel and this design: the two horizontal screws holding the Y-Idler come out right under the inner wheel holders and - and this is the bigger issue - they are too close together to allow a 20-tooth GT2 idler wheel to spin freely. There's two ways to get around this issue:

  • make the back-plate of the part much thicker to get the nuts far enough down to give the wheel enough clearance
  • drill two new holes into the P3Steel front plate (Use the drilling template for that. Arrow/Triangle points to top.)

I went with solution #2, mainly because it allows me to use any parts made for the Prusa MK3 on this machine too with very little changes. If you can't or don't want to drill any holes into your printer, please let me know and I'll do my best to design a "fat version" of the tensioner's back-plate to allow the wheel to spin freely.

Assembly & additional hardware needed can be found here: https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2786671

Hope the thing works as well for you as it does for me!

Please see dual magnetic hotend at work:

https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=eV0b1-vkH4U

I own a Zonestar P802Q2R printer. I needed dual hotend modification because of oozing and complicated dual hotend height setup. So i made this project, which solve it completelly and of course you can set exact height of each extruder by software. X axis rod space is 44mm.

This project uses only neodymium magnets, no electromagnets, so build and modification is easy as can be

3D Firmware modification
I did slight modification of standard Repetier 1.0 software in printer. I disable back move on X axis during X home process.

In 3D printer firmware parameters are configured a offsets of extruder 1 and 2.
EXT1 X_offset: 0 or -4160
EXT2 X_offset: 8320 or 4160

Components used

10x LM8UU linear bearings
https://www.aliexpress.com/item/LM8UU-Ball-Bearings-8mm-Bushing-3D-Printers-Parts-Rail-Linear-Long-Rod-Shaft-Part-8mm-15mm/32834611731.html

It should be used different type of fans... These does not have enough CFM

I got inductive sensor with Zonestar printer. On sensor is: TRZ-PL-08N, voltage 4-30V, sensing distance <=8mm

this should be same:

2x steel rod - oppositing each other in each extruder (principe of extruder interchange)
Ø 5mm, length 30.5mm

1x centering steel rod
Ø 5mm , length 45mm

1x M3 longer screw
M3 screw for installation into carrier to switch on X endstop during X homing

1x spring
spring for M3 X endstop carrier screw, installed under screw

2x 1.2-1.5mm aluminium sheet
aluminium sheet for left and right plates, which seal hotend nozzle during parking.
Dimensions, please see left and right plate.stl

This project uses a remix of four different project which are solving a needs of separate dual hotends.

Parking dual extruder by Jellebross
https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1446731

Dual parking carriage extruder by Helix3D
https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2201859

All parts are printable without supports. Recommended infill about 20-30%. Hotends mount should be printed from ABS or any other temperature resistant plastic. Rest of parts printed from PLA.

After printing is propably need to fine tune all holes:

  • it is good to drill all of 15mm holes for LM8UU bearings for bearings as bearing should fit perfectly into holes

please see pictures, which hole is centering and which hole is oppositing

  • drill 5.5mm centering holes in left and right extruder
  • drill 5.5mm oppositing hole in carrier
  • drill 5mm hole for centering rod in carrier
  • drill 5mm hole in left and right hotend for oppositing rods
  • drill/fine 6mm holes for all magnets, do not drill on bottom of hole, othervise you must stick magnets with glue!
  • magnets must touch each other to have good hold power, so install magnets at last step.

description.text:
This is a remix and refinement of Marcusmole's Steyr AC. This car is a truly unique vehicle, and the background is covered off here:

http://www.tanks-encyclopedia.com/ww2/nazi_germany/Austrian_ADGZ.php

I started with Marcusmole's file, but had some difficulty as it had the wheels and vehicle as all one part of the original file; I removed the wheels and corrected the inevitable damage to the file with Tinkercad, which is a trick as while Tinkercad does simple angles well, it does not do complex angles, and this vehicle is nothing but complex angles. I haven't yet worked on a file that I had so many "Work in Progress" files -

I added the side doors, vision slots, the rear hull MG, the wheel/tire combos, the front vents, added the exhaust pipes and turret hatches. I have all weapons - the 20mm cannon and coaxial and the two hull MGs - as separate items. Each has a fitting hole / nub on the model. The turret pivot ring is separate; I glued mine to the hull, but it works either way. I have found it stronger to have a separate piece joining the hull or turret as opposed to printing it as part of one or the other.

As always, be cautious with the small bits, and check the photos before gluing the turret weapons on; you don't want to get them on the wrong side.

In the Bolt Action rule set, this vehicle would have "recce" without a doubt; it is truly capable to going either direction without hesitation.

Please excuse the shiny black filament; it is a great filament but the photos don't do the model justice. I added a pic with a Soviet BA-10 for sense of scale. I don't own any Axis armies, but made this just because I think the original vehicle is such a thing of beauty.

I drew this up to hold a Microsoft LifeCam in order to take videos of my prints for family in my home town of Ottawa.  It works geat! Apply enough torque to the screw to hold the camera firmly but still allow for manual angle adjustment.  Be sure that the plastic bushing seats with the coupling end on the camera and that you don't over tighten the screw and strip it.  At that point you are essentially screwed. Pardon the pun..  
The mount has a recess for a 4mm nut and socket head screw for tightening it onto the rod. (This is reccomended but mine did fine without fasteners for a few prints before I put them in.)

The purpose of this design is to aid the process of installing and updating the Prusa i3 MK3 Einsy board with a directly attached Raspberry Pi Zero W via a rear accessible opening in the case.

I also addressed the following factors in this design:
• A simple removable door that is pressure fit to allow for easy toolless access.
• A small top cutout to allow removal of the RPi micro SD card using needle nose pliers.
• A right-side cutout to accommodate access to the upper USB port on the RPi.
• A left panel cutout to accommodate ribbon cable routing.
• An integrated stationary set of posts to hold the DCI cable extender in place and remove tension.

The case modification presented here is designed to work in conjunction with the Fixed Rear Camera Mount that I developed to attach the Raspberry Pi Camera V2.1 to the rear of the heated bed. See that part here:

https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2802597

For power cord I used an old iPhone charger cord, cut away the lightning adapter and soldered it to the fan. For power supply you can use just about anything that will accept a USB cable. You can either print one and dry one boot at the time but the smart thing is printing and assembling a pair and hook them up in parallell to the USB cable.

title: Connector for profile 6 (like Bosch) 20x40 90° with foot M6

description.text:
Changes 07 march 2018, 17:58 Berlin time.
The best way I found is to connect with a 6 mm dowel and 40 x Ø4 mm wood screw. The dowel must be inserted into the hole with a mallet. It runs very easily and does not create a problem. Then take the model where there is has now 4 angle joints. The connection is very robust and holds very well.
Changes 07 march 2018.New form of sockets. More stable.
The connector ensures the connection between 2 profiles 5 20x40 with 90 ° corner.
The connector saves expensive automatic connectors and makes the construction very simpatic.
It is required per one connector:
4 x M3 countersunk screws 16 mm;
1 x threaded foot;
2 x M6 nuts.
I recommend to buy a foot with steel core, but a STL file is also available here.
This design allows very slight horizontal adjustments of the printer.
Profile 6 has 2 holes with Ø5.3 mm, which allows without to cut M6 threads in these 2 holes.
Instead of threading, here is a split to 4 parts socket used, The socket has dowel function, If the screw is difficult to go into the hole, then it is recommended after inserting the bushes into the profile, an M3 thread in the sockets too to cut.
The foot has not been printed by me, but a similar part has already been successfully printed. This is a fairly small thread, so I would set the layer thickness to 0.1 mm and take the nozzle 0.2 mm. Although, in my opinion, a bought foot will fit much better.

This is a set of parts that make up the spindle for the Lomo Processing Tank. There are two distinct parts, the top and bottom pieces, that screw together to hold together the spiral reels that hold the film during processing.

There are 2 versions of the bottom spindle piece. The "ALT" version has a longer threaded extension than the original.

The original spindles are made from bakelite and are easily broken by dropping or over-forcing the threading while screwing the pieces together. The unfortunate soul in this situation is then left to either buy an entire new tank or make their own using parts from the hardware store.

The parts are generated using OpenSCAD scripts, with help from the threads and OpenSCAD Triangles libraries. The design is based on measurements of the original pieces, but I took as reference Replacement spindle for Lomo 100' 8/16/35mm film processing tank and Modified spindle for Lomo film processing tank. I had some difficulty with the prints and wanted to create the top part of the spindle as well.

This is a model of the first american satellite in space the Explorer 1.

It was launched February 1, 1958, 03:48 UTC and it discovered the Van Allen radiation belt by which wasnt planned and a big discovery.

This model is in 1:5 scale an is about 40cm tall. Slice it up in pieces you like to print it. There is a tube in the inside of the model so you could use the pin i included in the files to align the parts for gluing. For the antennas you could use 1mm steelwire.

PLA is suitable for the "clamp part".
The stand is included in two versions. As a complete model but like the rocket with a tube inside and also as a sliced version. I designed like the rocket with a tube inside that fits the pin used also for the rocket. So there is no need for supports a the stand as well.

If you guys thing the stand is to small just message me or write a comment and I will draw a bigger one. At the moment the stand isnt to big and holds the rocket really well.

FYI: I havent tested the wall mount yet, so there is a chance that i wont work but it should be fine.

I hope you like the model!

Depending on how accurate your printer is you may need to scale the pins. The holes for the antennas were a little to small. I heated up the antenna ends to push them in and than i secured them with a tiny drop of superglue that worked well. Again i hope this model will find some fans. title: Monoprice MP Select Mini Side Panel Spacer for Heated Bed Rewiring

description.text:
Monoprice MP Select Mini: Simplified no-drill Heated bed rewire mod with stock side panel

by vdub6127

For the uninitiated: the stock wiring under the heated bed routes the wires through the top of the chasis of the MP Select Mini. Over time will cause the wires to fray and wear as they rub against the sides of opening. A common and perhaps necessary modification is to route the wires externally around the back of the unit, allowing them to move freely without friction.

The current solutions for the heated bed rewire (while very clever) struck me as a tad "over-engineered". My goal was to carry out the same function of the modification with some other goals in mind:

  • Ease of installation
  • Reuse the perfectly good stock metal side panel and screws
  • Avoid drilling through the panel and voiding warranty
  • Minimal cosmetic change. Looks almost unchanged when done.
  • Minimize the need for more supplies such as wiring housings, grommets, etc.
  • Most importantly: avoid 4 hours of printing an entirely new panel. This design prints in about 45 mins

I made this possible by designing a 2mm spacer between the chasis and the side panel with a space that will allow the wires to pass through to the interior. I found that if the 4 wires are aligned vertically, they can comfortably squeeze through a 2mm gap in the side. Rather than enclosing the wires in a cable housing, I just opted for a few evenly-spaced zip-ties. In lieu of printing a "cable guide" to route the wires from under the bed, I opted for securing them down using the old standby: "electrical tape".

It is assumed that you'll be printing this on the mini itself, hence the split into two separate parts: front and back. The full one-piece version is also included.

Notes:

  • Since only the sides of the print is visible, you can make this print as ugly as you want and optimize for print speed. I used 0.2625 layer height and it was just fine.
  • This mod does make it a bit harder to get the SD cards in and out. I just use wifi or octoprint, so this has not been much of an issue to me. When I do need to get it out I just use the always nearby bed-leveling allan wrench to push it.
  • The 2mm width seemed to be enough clearance for the screws to catch the threads, but my first iteration (which was 2.5mm) had one screw that failed to catch, so it's pretty sensitive to width changes. Your mileage may vary.
  • In case there's concern about the wires rubbing on the on the side panel: on my printer, this has not been the case. When the bed is fully extended, it has plenty of slack and does not put any strain there. Again, YMMV.

Summary:

  • Edited Arms, eyes, coin with Mesh Mixer
  • Added details on feet, tail, coin, eyes, and cleaned the model in Virtual Reality (ShapeLab)
  • Printed
  • Airbrush painting
  • Brush painting for details
  • Gloss Varnished
  • Matt Varnished
  • Shots !

More than summary:

I like cryptocurrencies (especially Vertcoin which was the first to really make me dream back in 2017), and I like this character, so I decided to create a thing mixing both of these worlds.

That was the first time I used Virtual Reality to model finish something, and I have to say that the tools (ShapeLab for ex.) have made so much progress since last time I used it last year. It's stable, really precise, fun and so much easier to use than mesh mixer for modeling everything.

The model can be manipulated with one hand while applying modification with the other, like if we were doing pottery. We can move around the subject to observe every details. All the basic tools are available, such as grabing, moving, inflating, etc.. And the software was stable enough to handle a large model
I really enjoyed this part.

Before that, I used Mesh Mixer to re-arrange the shoulders (because I wasn't fan of the way they were shaped in the original model), putted hands out of the pocket and putted a coin in Nick's hand.

Had a hard time to print it, because I didn't want to put much support.. after one hour printing and failing miserably, I decided to continue with some supports, ant it went okay.

Then, I used airbrush to paint the big parts, easy, but I tend to rush a lot and not wait for a color to dry completely before beginning the next one (I hate waiting for these kind of things). So I had to begin again and again some color because wet paint don't really like the stickiness of the blue tape..

And then finished with my Vallejo set to paint the details. And this is it !

I included a version with VertCoin, and an other with neutral coin for the case you want to print your favorite coin instead of VTC (and because there is a lot of awesome other coins in the nature !).

Hope you enjoy,

description.text:
NOT RESPONSIBLE IF YOU CRACK OR SCRATCH YOUR SCREEN!!! USE AT YOUR OWN RISK.

I like to play some games on my iPad. One week after playing a little more than normal I noticed that my hands and forearms hurt. It felt like carpal tunnel. So I decided to create some ergonomic grips for the iPad that I can use when i play.

These Grips were designed using OnShape.com. It took me about 30 minutes so don't expect perfection. Since I was planning on using a flexible printed material I made the fit a little snug. exactly 6mm the same thickness of my iPad 4 mini. If you want to print using a more rigid material on an FDM printer use the 7mm version. Then I suggest you put something like a screen cloth in the gap so the glass is held by soft cloth instead of rigid plastic.

If you wish to customize it I have setup the onshape document for you to do that. You will need an onshape account. It is free. You will need to copy or clone my project so you can have a copy of your own that you can edit. Here is a link to mine. https://cad.onshape.com/documents/799699a6bba36c18de814134/w/e28d4b8a7da668fd72e9c75a/e/3f43d1b7d89bd5aee4cfdd50

After you open an editable copy of the document you will go to the tab called Part Studio 1. On the left side you will three variables that you can easily control. (X) #GapThickness is used to control how thick the gap is. aka how thick your tablet is. Keep in mind that a normal FDM printer is not very precise so you will need to give yourself some extra space. I suggest at least half a millimeter. (X) #SideBezelLip and Bottom is used to control how much space your side bezels take up. You can change the default values by double clicking the variable. Change the number in the small window that pops up and check the green box. You will see the drawings and 3D renderings update. When you are ready you will click on the parts in the parts list on the lower left side of the screen. They are called Left grip and Right grip. click on each of them one at a time then right click - Export.

Best of luck.

Formlabs Form 2 printer with Flexable V02

I printed the grips oriented as shown in the image. With SLA prints it is important to wash the parts in IPA for about 20 minutes. Then I rinsed the parts in water. At this point they were soft. I was able to use the knife to gently scrape excess material from the flat smooth fronts of the grips. The next thing to do was cut the supports off. The sharp knife was too dangerous so I used the snips or cutters. Please note that at this point I had NOT done any post curing with a UV light.

Removing the supports

As you can see there are MANY supports. These are required for this SLA printer when using a soft material.

Supports are cut. Next cut the nubs closer to the part.

I did a fast rough cut to get most of the supports removed. Then I came back and cut the nubs closer to the part. This makes it so I don't have to sand as much.

Sanding. I started sanding by hand and gave up.

I ended up using a sander with 120 grit. it still took about 8 minutes to smooth them out. I don't know if it would have been better to sand before or after I UV cured the parts. Because at this point the parts were soft. Later after I cured them the parts were a lot more firm.

Final steps.

I UV cured the parts at 60 degrees C for 60 minutes. They are firm but flexible. They fit my iPad nice and snug.

description.text: I designed these rockets for my son's Boy Scout patrol. They wanted to have a rocket launch and I thought it would be unique to design and make some that you couldn't buy. I have to date flown them on Estes A8-3 and B6-4 18mm motors. I used a 12in parachute for one flight and then tried a 1in x 30in streamer. Both worked perfectly.

Printer:

Anet A8

Rafts:

No

No

Resolution:

0.15mm

Infill:

100%

Notes:

I printed these using Inland 1.75mm PETG. I set to 240 deg on the extruder and 80 deg on the heat bed. Printed them at 50mm/sec. The rockets are pretty tough.

Instructions

Print (1) fin can, (1) body tube, (1) nozzle, and (1) nose cone. I used PETG. PLA and ABS would work as well. Not sure how the PLA would hold up to heat.

Note: Estes BT-50 body tube cut to 180mm works with the printed nose cone fin cans.

I found that very little filing and sanding was required to fit the fin can and nose cone into the tube. Leave the tube to fin can a tight fit. The nose cone I made a slip fit.

I used elastic chord for the shock chord. Tie 24in of elastic chord to the shock chord mount in the fin can. Slide the shock chord into the body tube and glue the body tube to the fin can using instant glue (Super Glue).

Tie the elastic to the nose cone. I tie an extra loop near the nose cone to attach the recovery system. When using a parachute, be sure to use a fishing swivel to reduce twisting. I also attach the streamer using a swivel as well.

Pre-Launch
I used (4) crumpled sheets of recovery wadding. Loosely packed the recovery system and installed the nose cone. Install the appropriate engine. {A8-3, B4-4, B6-4, C6-5, C6-7}. Note that with a B sized engine, the rocket goes quite high. Check the wind, chose an appropriate launch site, and be safe!!

Enjoy!

description.text:
Mar 7 2018: Added an STL file to print two small wrenches to assist adjustment of the contacts. See photos.

This is my take on a Morse Code sideswiper key, (also called cootie keys.) Unlike the traditional telegraph key which uses an up-and-down motion, the sideswiper makes contact on either side of a flexible arm, making for much less hand and wrist fatigue.

This key uses a short length of hacksaw blade as the lever arm; this is a ham radio tradition for these kind of keys, which were often home-brewed out of inexpensive materials on hand.

This key was inspired by the design found here: https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1662382

Notes:

You will get a little bridging in the wire vias, but it is easily cleaned out, and this is under the base and not visible when the key is in use.

I printed this in PETG and PLA - I like the PLA version better, less flexing.

What you will need

A piece of hacksaw blade about 125mm long.
brass or stainless steel #8 hardware for assembly.
brass or stainless steel #4 hardware to attach the finger pieces
about 2 feet of 20 or 22 ga solid wire

Prepare the hacksaw blade

Cut or break the blade to length (wear goggles!).
Sand off the paint on the blade. If you don't want to do the whole blade, make sure the portions where the supports and contacts are clean of paint.
You can use ScotchBrite to shine up the surface a bit after the paint is removed.
Finish the cut end with a file to remove sharp edges and burrs. (wear goggles!)
Measure 10mm from the cut end, and drill an 11/64th hole (5mm) centered on the blade. Go slow, the steel blade is hard. Wear goggles!

Preparing the connecting wires.

Break the shanks off of three #8 ring tongue terminals. Strip the insulation off one piece of 20 - 22 ga wire, this is the wire that will be used to connect to the hacksaw blade.

Solder the bare wire to one ring tongue, and two lengths of insulated 20 - 22 ga wire to the other two. See the photo.

Assemble the pieces

Poke the bare wire into the hole between the support pillars, slide the hacksaw blade in as well, and use an awl to line up the holes. Use the bolt, washers, and nut to secure the hacksaw blade - make sure it is level, and tighten securely.

Drop a wire with a ring tongue on it through each of the wire holes, on the base just inside the contact pillars.

Thread a nut all the way onto each of the contact bolts, and add a flat washer. Push the assembly through the contact holes and place the ring tongue over it on the inside of the pillar. Add a nut to secure the assembly. You can change the contact spacing by adjusting the nuts to give the right spacing when both nuts are tightened.

Attach the finger pieces to the end of the blade with the #4 screw, washers and nut.

I wanted the support and contacts as close to the base as possible to reduce flexing. I thickened the supports to make them more rigid.
Also, the connecting wires are routed internal to the support pillars, which makes them less visible.

This design was done using Fusion 360.

description.text:
After searching for a x-axis belt tensioner, I was unable to find one that fit my Zonestar Z8XM2.
The closest one I found that worked with a bit of sanding was the CR-10 X-Axis Realigned Tensioner. Which is where the knob came from, Thanks!
Basically I used that model as inspiration and drew up a new belt tensioner from scratch using Fusion 360. The Fusion 360 model is also included if you wanna change it up.

To assemble the tensioner, you will need a M5 hex head bolt around 25 or 30mm long and a standard M5 nut for the knob and puller. You may break things if you use a nylon lock nut here and it's simply not needed. I also put a washer between the cap and knob, but it's not really needed either.
I used an extra M5 pan head bolt, around 20mm or so from the printer's kit and an M5 nylon lock nut to mount the bearing in the puller with the nut towards the outside. The head of the bolt needs to be 3mm or less in depth so it doesn't hit the printer as it slides. The bearing is simply the one that came with the printer.

The bent tensioner is held in place by the tension of the belt, no screws or anything else required. It's been really sturdy for me and I've not had any issues with it moving or loosening.

This thing has made a HUGE difference with my prints. My circles were never round before I installed this. I also used the Adjustable GT2 belt tensioner for my Y-Axis. It works well enough, but I'll eventually make a tensioner with an adjustable knob like this one I designed for the X-Axis.

Hopefully this helps. If it does, feel free to leave a tip!
Enjoy!

title: Anet A8 Y-Axis Belt Tension Improver

description.text:
Totally Mislabeled this when I uploaded, THIS IS FOR THE Y-AXIS sorry for the confusion.

Found some of the other Y-Axis tensioners wouldn't accept an actual idler pulley, smooth or toothed. So I designed this tensioner to accept these Toothed Pulleys and these Smooth Pulleys from Amazon.com.
There are a couple advantages over the stock bearings, With these pulleys, they are a single unit which means no more squeezing the belt under tension which will alleviate some excess friction and in some cases light clicking. If you move to a toothed pulley the belt will exit the pulley smoother, this is due to the belt engaging fully on the idler pulley as opposed to just on the crown of each tooth. In some cases, this can eliminate fine chatter in prints.

ORIGINAL BY sumbloke. YOU CAN VIEW HIS QR CODE GENERATOR HERE.

This remix fixes an issue where a model would not compile when this QR-code generator is used as a library in another OpenSCAD file:

use <QR_generator.scad>;

It probably fixes the issue that causes the Thingiverse Customizer to crash as well, but I won't know until the Customizer is back up.

I might look into expanding the functionality of this OpenSCAD program (if the original author doesn't), because I like not having to deal with nasty scripts to use QR-codes in your designs.

The original OpenSCAD file included a custom function to convert a raw byte to its numerical value. This was implemented by providing a string that includes all (extended) ASCII characters, even non-printable ones, and searching through it to find the given byte/character and return its index.

The problem with this implementation is that not all software supports using extended ASCII characters. Rendering just this OpenSCAD file itself doesn't result in an error, but including it as a library in another model causes it to fail. Apparently, somewhere in the software responsible for copying the source of other OpenSCAD files to use it as libraries, there is a part that only supports signed characters (values ranging from 1 to 127). Probably this holds also true for the Thingiverse Customizer.

This problem was fixed by re-implementing this function. It now tries to recursively find the numerical value of a character. By doing it this way, there are no non-printable characters in the source of the OpenSCAD file.

remixed_from.title: Mini and Triple Pocket Hole Jig

description.text:
Printed the triple pocket hole jig by 1976westy, and decided to make it into a kreg k4 style jig.

There are some very subtle register on the stand to help line it up with the setback for different thickness of lumber.

To make this you will need the following items:

  • a few piece of 1x4 wood
  • toggle clamp ( I use https://www.amazon.com/gp/product/B004K60H08/ref=oh_aui_detailpage_o04_s00?ie=UTF8&psc=1 )
  • wood screw
  • glue
  • saw

After you printed the stand, mount it to the wood base, adjust position of toggle clamp and fix it in place.

If you are going to use it with the 1/2" thick board, you might want to chisel out a 1/4" deep socket for the jig to drop lower than the board.

I make the T shape base for support of wider board with lap joint and wood glue. If you want a compact jig, just a piece of straight 1x4 would do. With the T shape base, it kinda is a cross over between kreg k4 and k5.

Now you can build everything with pocket hole...

Thanks 1976westy for the design!

Safety-wise, drinking from a 3d-printed cup depends on factors like the type of filament used, lead free extrusion (i.e. using nozzle that isn't made of brass), and possibly a food safe epoxy/coating.

I printed with an FDA Compliant filament: Formfutura HDglass, which is similar to PETG. And then coated it with a food-safe epoxy. This gave my model a nice shine and added additional transparency to the print.

The model itself stands 5 in tall. The diameter of the base is 2.5 in. The opening at the top is 3.5 in diameter. The base and wall thickness is 3 mm.
